We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:

a) The Accountable Officers to justify the dormant inventories, which are under their accountability and are no longer existing and submit an application of relief from accountability with supporting documents, if warranted, otherwise, they shall be held accountable for the cost of these inventories;

b) The Accountable Officers to submit a certified list of Recipients with their actual receipt, unless circumstances may justify absence of actual receipt; 

c) The General Services Officer to – 

• Prepare the forms prescribed by the Manual on NGAS for LGUs with supporting documents from the accountable officers and ensure submission to Accounting Office promptly to effect actual issuance to recipients and recognize any unissued stocks;

• Conduct physical count of Inventories and prepare the RPCI with sufficient and relevant details; and

d) The General Services Officer and Municipal Accountant to resolve the discrepancies of inventory balances between their records and update their respective reports in order to ensure that the inventories are fully accounted for and recognized accurately in the books.

We recommended the Management to ensure that:

a) Cash balances are sufficient to settle currently maturing obligations and available for special trust funds and for other appropriations.

b) Long outstanding and unclaimed checks as well as unreleased and stale checks are properly adjusted as at year-end;

c) All adjustments against the cash accounts shall be supported with  proper documents;

d) Reconciliation between the Accounting, Budget and Treasury Offices is undertaken regularly; and

e) Cash accounts are monitored consistently and should be presented fairly in accordance with IPSAS 1 and other accounting rules and regulations.

We recommended the following to the Management:

a) Re-assess the estimates of revenues and expenses in the Annual Budget and present a more realistic and attainable projections in order to avoid falling short of actual collections and fund resources;

b) Devise concrete plans and strategies that shall be effective in monitoring the existence and availability of cash before incurrence of expenditures; 

c) Consider adopting austerity measures on expenditures vis-à-vis available cash and other fiscal resources; 

d) Ensure that the balances of appropriation/allotment coincide with and be properly supported by certified available cash before committing/obligating and disbursing funds; and

e) Ensure that that the indications of possible cash deficit observed in audit be resolved timely and its occurrence should be avoided.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require:

a) The Inventory Committee to prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System and the General Services Officer to render a Report on Local Road Network and maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map;

b) The Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries in the books pertaining to the misclassifications, transfer of Construction in Progress assets already completed to their proper asset accounts, non-depreciation, and unreconciled differences;

c) The Municipal Accountant to conduct periodic reconciliation of CIP accounts with those completed projects and prepare and maintain a CIP-Ledger Cards on a per project basis, and henceforth, ensure that in recording transactions, the proper accounts are used;

d) The Municipal Accountant to evaluate and review the recognition principle for disbursements and effect necessary adjusting entry for the reclassification of expenses to appropriate asset accounts and corresponding depreciation expenses; and

e) Compliance by all concerned official with the aforementioned rules and regulations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor to:

a) Direct the above-mentioned key officials to accomplish the duties and responsibilities assigned to them;

b) Ensure compliance with accounting and reporting guidelines set forth in COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 25, 2015.

We recommended Management:

a) Require the concerned employees to submit the lacking documents and justify the above-noted payments which are not within the scope and coverage of EO 298;

b) Ensure that payments of traveling expenses 1) conform to the prescribed allowable rates and be documented in accordance with the above-stated law and rules, 2) will involve the most economical expenditure and 3) cover only those that are urgent and extremely necessary.

We recommended the following:

a) The LCE must ensure that the GFPS members are well-trained and equipped with the required gender capabilities, such as the application of gender analysis and monitoring tools;

b) The GAD Focal Person and members of the Technical Working Group use monitoring tools such as the HGDG and PIMME in monitoring and evaluating GAD activities and submit to the Audit Team the annual accomplishment report for evaluation;

c) The Management should mainstream and incorporate GAD concerns in their local development plans; and

d) Utilization of the GAD budget should be in accordance with the DILG-approved GAD Plan and Budget.

We recommended the Management to:
Require both the General Services Officer and the Municipal Accountant to resolve the identified variances in their respective reports and require them the submission of reconciled records and reports in compliance with COA Circular No. 2020-006;
Require the Municipal Engineering Office to submit reports on completed projects and its supporting documents regularly to the Municipal Accounting Office to facilitate the recognition of completed projects;
The Municipal Accountant to properly recognize capitalizable repair in the books of accounts of the Municipality;
Reclassify the fuel expense incurred for the LGU village in its appropriate expense account;
Prepare necessary Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment (ARE) for purchased equipment and issue the same to the end-users of these equipment to establish accountability over these properties;
Conduct periodic reconciliation of CIP accounts with those completed projects and prepare and maintain CIP-Ledger Cards on a per-project basis, and henceforth, ensure that in recording transactions, the proper accounts are used.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the following:
The accountable employees and officials to refund the excess payment of TLB;
The Municipal Treasurer monitor their payments and submits the duplicate copy of the Official Receipt and validated deposit slip;
The Municipal Human Resource Management Officer perform an intensive review of the leave cards, Daily Time Records, Certificate of Attendance – for Sanggunian Bayan Members and Application for Leave and deduct any unrecorded undertime, tardiness, and absences before certifying the photocopy of leave cards and issuing a certificate of leave credits which will serve as the variable in calculating the TLB and to avoid overpayment of TLB; and
Review the overpayment/ underpayment of TLB and prepare necessary Adjusting Journal Entry to recognize the effect of overpayment/ underpayment of TLB for CY 2022.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the following officials:
Municipal Engineer
Accomplish the Program of Works for the projects of 20% DF before the preparation of the Annual Budget;
Monitor the implementation of projects and ensure the adherence to plans, targets, and performance indicators;
Expedite the unimplemented 20% DF projects and ensure the timely completion of the 20% DF projects;
OIC - Municipal Planning and Development Officer
Specify the expected start date and completion dates of the PPA of 20% DF in the Annual Investment Plan for the concrete basis of other work plans; and
Evaluate the implementation of 20% DF programs and projects in accordance with the approved development and investment plan.
The Municipal Engineer and Local Finance Committee prepare the Quarterly Physical Report of Operations and Physical and Financial Performance Evaluation Form, respectively, as required in the Budget Operation Manual for LGU, 2016 edition, for them to assess the plans and targets of projects of 20% DF; and
The Municipal Budget Officer assists the Municipal Engineer in the preparation of the required reports stated in the BOM for LGU and adheres to the preparation of Allotment Release Orders.

We recommended that the Management:
Review the E-trike Deployment Plan and prepare necessary action to address issues that will be established during the review;
Comply on the provision on the Deed of Donation specifically on notifying the DOE on the non-compliance on of the terms as provided in the Deployment Plan and prepare and submit required reports to DOE;
Create a fact-finding committee that will assess the presence or absence of negligence on the part of the recipients/ operator of the E-trikes on the missing units, missing parts, and damages to the units, and determine their liability, if any; and
Recall all e-trike units issued to non-qualified recipients and issue them to those specifically mentioned qualified users as provided in the MOA between DOE and the LGU.

We recommended that the Municipality of Echague to require the following officers:
Municipal Human Resource Management Officer
Deduct the undertime, tardiness, and under-recorded leave credits during absences in the compressed work week arrangement of personnel for the calendar year 2022 and the absences during regular sessions of Sangguniang Bayan Officials from the calendar year 2018 to 2022 and the following years to their cumulative earned leave credits;
Submit a copy of the resolution of elected officials for the non-availment of 5-day mandatory leave or else, it shall be deducted from their cumulative earned leave credits;
Provide a biometric system in the offices far from the Municipal Hall and enroll all the personnel of the LGU in the system;
Enforce strictly the proper filing of leave of absence and use the prescribed form which is CSC Form No. 6, revised 2020; and
Assess the efficiency and effectiveness of the implementation of the compressed workweek arrangement and formulate additional policies to attain the objectives of adopting the compressed workweek arrangement.
Municipal Accountant
Evaluate the daily time record, certificate of attendance during regular sessions – for Sangguniang Bayan Members, approved applications for leave, and other documents related to the official business/travel of personnel and officials and use as basis in the preparation of payrolls for the payment of their salaries and attached these documents to the payrolls; and
Ensure the completeness of supporting documents to be attached to the payroll.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor to require:

a) The Municipal Accountant to re-evaluate the claims with incomplete documents and require submission of proper documents, otherwise in the absence of documents to support basis of payment or settlement, derecognize the liabilities; 

b) The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to expedite the return of the unexpended balances of fund transfers to the Source Agencies;

c) The concerned department heads or officials to submit pertinent documents in cases that the projects and activities may still be implemented within the next accounting period otherwise, the return of the funds to the Source Agencies or donors should be undertaken; 

d) The Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer pay or settle those liabilities which are due to barangays, employees and other claimants who can fully establish the legal basis for their unpaid accounts; and

e) The Municipal Accountant to recognize only those liabilities with valid claims, legal basis and supporting documents in accordance with accounting principles set forth by IPSAS 19 and PD 1445

We recommended the Management to ensure that the following courses of action are undertaken and thereafter submit documents showing compliance thereof:

a) Not less than 5% of the total estimated revenue from regular sources are appropriated for LDRRMF and this appropriation should be funded with available cash in order to guarantee available funds in times of disaster and other calamities;

b) The CY 2020 unexpended balances of LDRRMF as well as the funds received in trust for LDRRM are transferred and established as Special Trust Funds in the Trust Liabilities-DRRMF in the Trust Fund books;

c) Proper adjustments both in the books and in the budget reports be made to reflect the accurate balances of the LDRRMF as at December 31, 2020;

d) The LDRRMF Investment Plan with details on prior years’ unexpended balances, Inventory reports and other pertinent documents are prepared in accordance with the LDRRMF guidelines;

e) Gather and submit for proper evaluation in audit the summary/list of donations received and distributed with supporting documents; and

f) All concerned officials comply with the aforementioned laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended Management to:

a) Require both the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to perform regular reconciliation of accounting records with the cashbook to address and account for any discrepancies thereat;

b) Ensure the receipt of Bank Statements monthly or request copies of monthly snapshots to facilitate preparation of Bank Reconciliation Statements promptly and in order that reconciling items be identified and adjusted accordingly;

c) Make necessary and appropriate adjustments for the long-outstanding book reconciling items based on a pertinent document to come up with the correct balance of Cash in Bank accounts; 

d) Improve cash management to avoid incurrence of cash deficits and assertively pursue feasible solutions that can address the issue involving fiscal operations of the Municipality; and

e) Comply with the reportorial requirements as prescribed by the above-cited rules and regulations.

We recommended Management to:

a) Strictly utilize the Quick Response Fund with a duly supported Declaration of State of Calamity stating thereat the specific criteria as enumerated in NDRRMC Memorandum Order No. 60, s. 2019 dated June 17, 2019;

b) Ensure the timely implementation of projects and utilization of funds to be able to efficiently deliver the immediate needs and relief of calamity or disaster victims;

c) Efficiently implement programs, projects and activities that are within the LDRRMP and AIP or to its supplemental or revised plans, if any;

d) Require the Municipal Budget Officer to prepare and maintain Registry of Appropriation, Allotments and Obligations for QRF, MOOE and Capital Outlay; and

e) Strictly and prudently comply with all the rules and regulations laid out relative to LDRRM Fund.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor to:

a) Demand the 53 Punong Barangays and their Barangay Treasurers to liquidate the outstanding fund transfers and submit all the supporting documents as enumerated in COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;

b) Require the Punong Barangays and the Barangay Treasurers to justify the non-implementation of the purpose of the fund transfers. Otherwise, direct them to return the funds to the LGU in order that these funds will be used for other priority programs and projects.

